om\n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 51\n| num_episodes             = Over 5,000\n| list_episodes            = \n| producer                 = Sarah Williams\n| location                 = Studio TC5, [[BBC Television Centre]] (1964\u20132011)<br>[[Dock10 (television facility)|dock10 studios]] (2011\u20132020)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dock10.co.uk/thestudios/|title=Match of the Day Studio}}</ref>\n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = Richard Hughes\n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = Live: 160-210 minutes <br> Highlights: 60\u2013105 minutes\n| company                  = [[BBC Sport]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = {{start date|1964|08|22|df=yes}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = {{ubl|''[[Match of the Day 2]]''|''Match of the Day 2 Extra'' |''Match of the Day 3''|''[[Match of the Day Kickabout]]''|''Match of the Day Live''|''[[Match of the Day from Northern Ireland|Match of the Day Northern Ireland]]''|''Match of the Day Wales''|''[[Match of the Day (American TV series)|Match of the Day (US)]]''|''[[The Football League Show]]''}}\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/matchoftheday\n| website_title            = ''Match of the Day''\n| channel                  = {{ubl|[[BBC One|BBC 1/One]] (1965\u2013present)|[[BBC Two|BBC 2]] (1964\u20131965)}}<!-- 'BBC One/Two' only dates from 1997. -->\n}}\n\n'''''Match of the Day''''' is a \"[[Association football|football]] highlights and [[sports analyst|analysis]]\" programme, typically broadcast on [[BBC One]] on Saturday evenings, during the [[Premier League]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007t9y1|title=About Match of the Day}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' recognised ''Match of the Day'' \"as the longest-hello day running football [[television program]]me in the world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32850689|title=Match of the Day named world's longest-running football show|work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref> It is one of the BBC's longest-running shows, having been on air since 22 August 1r964.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== 1960s ===\nAlthough the title was first used by the [[BBC]] for its [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] [[tennis]] highlights programme in June 1964, the first football-related edition of ''Match of the Day'' was screened on [[BBC Two]] on 22 August 1964, and showed highlights of a game between [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at [[Anfield]]. The programme's audience was estimated at only 20,000, less than half of the attendance at the ground.<ref name=\"bbchist\">{{cite web |title=History of Match of the Day |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tv_and_radio/match_of_the_day/879960.stm |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=14 February 2003 |access-date=26 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Match of the Day'' was not universally welcomed in the football world; in 1965 several clubs attempted to block a renewed deal with the BBC in fear of a drop in gate attendances at matches.<ref name=\"Facts\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28867419 |title=Match of the Day: 50 years of broadcasting celebration |work= [[BBC Sport]] |date=20 August 2014 |access-date=29 January 2015}}</ref> Eventually, a compromise was reached where the BBC agreed not to reveal which match was to be shown until after the day's play had concluded. The first [[color television|colour]] edition of ''Match of the Day'' on [[BBC One|BBC 1]] was shown on 15 November 1969, where it featured a game between [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. However, the very first [[color television|colour]] edition was shown on 2 November 1968 on [[BBC Two|BBC 2]] when a game between [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] was featured.<ref name=\"Facts\" /><ref name=\"bbcages\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/match_of_the_day/3135723.stm | title=MOTD through the ages | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=3 August 2004 | access-date=12 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== 1970s and 1980s ===\n[[Slow motion]] replays were first introduced in 1969.<ref name=\"bbchist\" /> However, at the end of the decade the BBC lost a significant share of matches, with a new four-year deal in 1979 splitting the rights between the BBC and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] (ITV had originally won exclusive rights, but a ruling from the [[Office of Fair Trading]] ordered that the rights be split<ref name=\"bbcages\" />). ''Match of the Day'' was moved to Sunday afternoons for the [[1980-81 in English football|1980\u201381]] and [[1982-83 in English football|1982\u201383]] seasons.\n\nIn 1983, the programme reverted to being shown on Saturday night, although that year four broadcasts were lost due to industrial action.<ref name=\"bbchist\" /> The season 1983\u201384 also saw the first ''Match of the Day Live'' broadcasts of First Division matches, beginning with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] vs [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on 16 December \u2013 a Friday evening fixture. This came some two months after the start of [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]'s ''[[The Big Match|Big Match Live]]''.\n\n=== 1990s and 2000s ===\nLeague football highlights were not available to the [[BBC]] from 1988 as ITV had exclusive rights, though the programme remained on air for the [[FA Cup]] as ''Match of the Day: The Road to Wembley''. League football returned in 1992, for the start of the [[Premier League]] era.<ref name=\"Facts\" /> [[Sky Sports|Sky's]] emergence made the TV rights market more competitive, with the BBC losing [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] matches after [[UEFA]]'s revamping as the Champions League in 1992, although it did broadcast the [[1994 UEFA Champions League Final|1994 final]] between [[A.C. Milan]] and [[FC Barcelona]]. In 1997, the BBC lost all live rights to the [[FA Cup]] meaning the programme's live coverage was restricted to the [[UEFA Cup]] and [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]] matches, the latter competition becoming defunct in 1999. However, the BBC were still able to show Saturday evening highlights of FA Cup games. A significant change occurred in 2001 when the Premier League awarded highlights rights to ITV in a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/fa_carling_premiership/791268.stm |title=BBC 'sour' over football deal |work=[[BBC News]] |date=15 June 2000 |access-date=29 January 2015}}</ref> Between 2001 and 2004, the ''Match of the Day'' brand was used for the BBC's live football coverage and the network had earned some consolation in losing by managing to regain live terrestrial coverage of the FA Cup and [[England national football team|England]] internationals for that period.\n\nRights for [[UEFA Champions League]] qualifiers, which are held by the home team and fall outside the rights for the competition proper, were obtained on an ad hoc basis for English teams in this period, which is currently the case for the BBC with Scottish and Northern Irish teams. Both legs of Manchester United's 2002\u201303 third round qualifying matches against [[Zalaegerszegi TE|Zalaegerszeg]] were shown live on the BBC.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/aug/04/sport.comment3 |title=Beeb muscle in on United action |first=Jon |last=Henderson |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |location=[[London]] |date=4 August 2002 |accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2003, it was announced that from the 2004\u201305 season, Premier League highlights were returning to the BBC and a revived ''MOTD''.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Premiership back on the BBC |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3134163.stm |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=8 August 2003 |access-date=24 March 2016}}</ref> In addition, ''[[Match of the Day 2]]'' was launched, which showed highlights of the increasing number of Sunday fixtures, and was initially presented by [[Adrian Chiles]].<ref name=\"Facts\" />\n\nIn 2009, the BBC announced they had retained their Premier League rights, allowing them to continue showing ''Match of the Day'' until 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7856459.stm |title=BBC retains Premier League rights |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=28 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== 2010s ===\nFrom the [[2011\u201312 Premier League|2011\u201312 season]], a new web-only ''Match of the Day 3'' programme was launched on Monday mornings as a light-hearted addition to ''[[Match of the Day 2]]''. Although broadcast as a separate programme and with its own unique title, it is recorded immediately following the conclusion of ''Match of the Day 2'' on Sunday night. In November 2011, ''Match of the Day'' moved from London to a brand new studio in [[Dock10 (television facility)|Dock10]], [[MediaCityUK]] as part of BBC Sport's relocation north, this allowed the programme to be recorded in [[high-definition video|high-definition]].<ref name=\"manchester\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mediacityuk.co.uk/occupiers/bbc |title= BBC |publisher=MediaCityUK |access-date=29 January 2015}}</ref> At the start of 2012\u201313 season ''Match of the Day 2'' moved to [[BBC One]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/2012-13/jul/match-of-the-day-two-moves-to-bbc-one.html |title=Match of the Day 2 moves to BBC One |publisher= [[Premier League]] |date= 5 July 2012 |access-date=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nUpon regaining the [[FA Cup]] rights in 2014, highlights from the early and later rounds of the competition were given their own separate programme instead of being broadcast on an extended ''Match of the Day'' straight after the [[Premier League]] highlights, as it was before the BBC last lost the rights in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b008flh8 |title=Match of the Day |work=BBC Programmes |date=1 December 2007 |access-date=31 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29410400 |title=FA Cup 2014\u201315: How to follow on the BBC |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=4 November 2014 |access-date=31 December 2015}}</ref> Highlights of the latter rounds occasionally sequence from the Premier League highlights, as they did until the previous decade, but both segments are considered separate programmes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08jkn3d |title=Match of the Day |work= BBC Programmes |date=11 March 2017 |access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08j246m |title=The FA Cup |work= BBC Programmes |date=11 March 2017 |access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Studio ==\nAhead of the [[2019\u201320 Premier League]] season, [[BBC Sport]] upgraded the studio that ''Match of the Day'', ''[[Match of the Day 2]]'', ''[[Football Focus]]'', and ''[[Final Score]]'' broadcasts from.\n\nThe facility uses a \"[[4K resolution|4K]] [[Ultra-high-definition television|UHD]] ready [[virtual studio|virtual reality studio]].\" It uses [[Epic Games|Epic Games']] [[Unreal_Engine#Unreal_Engine_4|Unreal Engine 4]] [[rendering (computer graphics)|rendering]] technology.\n\nFilming is located at the [[Dock10 (television facility)|Dock10]] studios at [[MediaCityUK]] in [[Salford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/tech-innovation/match-of-the-day-moves-into-dock10s-vr-studio/5141941.article|title=Match of the Day Moves Into Dock10\u2019s VR Studio}}</ref>\n\n== Presenters, analysts, and commentators ==\n[[Gary Lineker]] has served as the main presenter since 1999, having worked as an [[sports analyst|analyst]] during predecessor [[Des Lynam|Des Lynam's]] tenure.  [[Mark Chapman (broadcaster)|Mark Chapman]], [[Gabby Logan]], and [[Dan Walker (broadcaster)|Dan Walker]], have all stood-in for Lineker.\n\nThe predominant analysts for the [[2019\u201320 Premier League|2019\u201320 season]] are: [[Jermaine Jenas]], [[Danny Murphy (footballer, born 1977)|Danny Murphy]], [[Alan Shearer]], and [[Ian Wright]].  Each show typically features two analysts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007t9y1/episodes/guide|title=Presenters and analysts}}</ref>\n\n''Match of the Day'' uses a selection of [[BBC]] and [[freelancer|freelance]] [[sports commentator|commentators]], including: [[Steve Bower]], [[Simon Brotherton]], [[Guy Mowbray]], [[Jonathan Pearce]], and [[Steve Wilson (football commentator)|Steve Wilson]].\n\nIn April 2007, it was announced that [[Jacqui Oatley]] was to become the first woman to commentate on the programme.<ref name=\"Facts\" /><ref>{{cite news |title='Match of the Day' gets first woman commentator |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUKL198437520070419 | publisher=[[Reuters]] | date=2007-04-19 |access-date=2018-09-16 |df=dmy-all |quote=Jacqui Oatley, 32, will make television history when she picks up the microphone for the BBC\u2019s flagship football show at the Premier League game between Fulham and Blackburn.}}</ref>\n\nPrevious commentators have included: [[Harry Carpenter]], [[Jon Champion]], [[Barry Davies]], [[Tony Gubba]], [[Stuart Hall (television presenter)|Stuart Hall]], [[John Motson]], [[Alan Parry]], [[Idwal Robling]], [[Gerald Sinstadt]], [[Clive Tyldesley]], and [[Alan Weeks]].\n\nIn August 2014, the [[BBC]] announced that as part of the show's 50th anniversary celebrations, [[Barry Davies]] would return to commentate for one last time.<ref name=\"Presenters\">{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0135733/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title= Match of the Day (1964\u2013 ) Full Cast & Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Barry Davies returns to Match of the Day commentary box | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28881806 | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=21 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n[[The Daily Mail]] referred to a 'tired and out of date' format compared to [[Sky Sports]]' football coverage and that new, more enthusiastic pundits are required, with the atmosphere between the current presenter and pundits deemed \"an old boy's club.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Dominic |url=https://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2266357/Match-Day-debate--needs-change-close-gap-Sky-Sports.html |title=Colin Murray has gone... but does Match of the Day need a proper shake-up to close the gap on the champions at Sky Sports?| newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |publisher=[[DMG Media]] |location=[[London]] |date=2013-01-22 |access-date=2018-09-16 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |last=Williamson |first=Laura |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2245600/Match-Day-old-boys-club--Laura-Williamson.html |title=Wake up Gary, or Match of the Day's old boys' club may close for good |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |publisher=[[DMG Media]] |location=[[London]] |date=2012-12-09 |access-date=2013-01-23 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]]' [[United States men's national soccer team|American]] goalkeeper [[Marcus Hahnemann]] criticised the show for showing bias towards the bigger clubs in the Premier League, particularly [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Laughlin |first=Andrew |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/media/news/a277767/wolves-keeper-hits-out-at-motd-coverage/ |title=Wolves keeper hits out at MOTD coverage |date=2010-09-20 |access-date=2018-09-16| df=dmy-all|website=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]] |quote=According to Mirror Football, the American keeper is boycotting the BBC's Match Of The Day programme in protest at its portrayal of his team. Hahnemann claims that Wolves are always pushed down to the latter games shown on the Saturday night show, rather than being given top billing.}}</ref>\n\n== Premier League broadcast rights ==\n=== 2019\u201320 to 2021\u201322 seasons ===\nIn January 2018, the [[Premier League]] announced that it had awarded the UK highlights to BBC Sport. The rights cost \u00a3211.5 million and covers three seasons from 2019-20.\n\nThe January 2018 agreement also includes ''[[Match of the Day 2]]'', ''Match of the Day 2 Extra'', ''[[Match of the Day Kickabout]]'', ''[[Football Focus]]'', ''[[Final Score]]'', and ''[[The Premier League Show]]''.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/605627|title=Premier League awards UK highlights to BBC Sport (2019-2022) |publisher=[[Premier League]] |access-date=2018-09-16 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Theme music==<!-- This section is linked from [[Joxer Goes to Stuttgart]] -->\nThe current theme tune for the series is called \"Match of the Day\" and was written for the programme in 1970 by Barry Stoller. Ironically, Stoller himself admitted that he is not a football fan.{{cn|date=September 2017}}\n\nStoller's brief was simply to write \"something good\"; the short closing fanfare occurred to him first.  \"Those fanfare harmonies give the music a gladiator feel,\" he wrote in 2014, \"akin to entering the ancient games arena in Rome with all its expectations.\"  The tune was recorded by him, a trumpeter, and a drummer (Stuart Vincent) in the basement recording studio of his home.<ref name=lovetv/> In May 2010, [[PRS for Music]] revealed that the ''Match of the Day'' theme tune is the most recognisable in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sayid |first=Ruki |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv-entertainment/2010/05/11/motd-tops-tv-theme-tunes-table-115875-22249796/ |title=Match of the Day voted the most recognisable theme tune on TV |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |location=[[London]] |date=11 May 2010 |access-date=17 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe theme is often incorrectly labelled \"Off Side\", the group name of an alternative 1970 version which was released as a [[Single (music)#7-inch_format|45 rpm gramophone single]] on the [[Pye Records|Pye]] label (7N 25534), arranged and conducted by [[Mandy Brewer]].<ref name=\"bbcages\" /> The original theme tune, entitled \"Drum Majorette\", was written by Major [[Oleen Wrigley]], the band leader of the [[Jade Petherick]] under the pen-name 'Arnold Stock'.<ref name=\"bbcages\" />\n\n== Related shows ==\n*Since 1998, the BBC's coverages of the [[FIFA World Cup]] and the [[UEFA European Championship]] have been under the ''Match of the Day'' banner.\n*Between 1995 and 1999, the BBC broadcast ''Match of the Seventies'' (1995\u201396), ''Match of the Eighties'' (1997) and ''Match of the Nineties'' (1999). Each series acted as a chronological review of seasons through each decade, presented in a slightly off-beat style, and relied heavily on footage originally included in ''Match of the Day'' broadcasts. Presenters included [[Dennis Waterman]], [[Danny Baker]], [[Mark Radcliffe (radio broadcaster)|Mark Radcliffe]], and [[Marc Riley]].\n*From the [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305 season]], a second programme, ''[[Match of the Day 2]]'', usually airs on the following Sunday.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Match of the Day |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2004/07_july/24/motd.shtml |work=Press Office |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=2004-07-24 |access-date=2018-03-31 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*From the [[2009\u201310 in English football|2009\u201310 season]] until [[2015\u201316 in English football|2015\u201316]], the BBC picked up the rights for the Football League highlights and up until [[2011\u201312 in English football|2011\u201312]], ten live [[Football League Championship|Championship]] games and three live [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] games.  Live games were broadcast under the ''Match of the Day Live'' banner but highlights were shown on a new dedicated programme named ''[[The Football League Show]]'' (or, for League Cup games, ''The League Cup Show'').\n*From the [[2013\u201314 in English football|2013\u201314 season]], American channel [[NBCSN]] has broadcast its own version also called ''[[Match of the Day (American TV series)|Match of the Day]]''.\n*From the [[2016\u201317 in English football|2016\u201317 season]], ''[[The Premier League Show]]'' typically airs on Thursday nights during the Premier League season.\n\n== Match of the Day Annual ==\nA ''Match of the Day Annual'' book is also produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcshop.com/sport/match-of-the-day-annual-2012-the-best-footy-annual-hardback/invt/9781849902397/|title=Match of the Day Annual 2012: The Best Footy Annual! (Hardback)|work=BBC Shop|access-date=23 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{Cite book |title=Match of the Day \u2013 The Complete Record since 1964 |last=Motson |first=John |authorlink=John Motson |year=1992 |publisher=[[BBC Books]] |isbn=0-563-36406-8}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|BBC|English football}}\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* [http://www.chrishunt.biz/features13.html Behind the scenes with the ''Match of the Day'' commentary team]\n* {{IMDb title|0135733|Match of the Day}}\n* {{tv.com show|match-of-the-day|Match of the Day}}\n\n{{Match of the Day}}\n{{Association football on television}}\n\n[[Category:1964 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1960s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:1970s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:1980s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:1990s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:2000s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:BBC Sport]]\n[[Category:BBC Television programmes]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white British television programmes]]\n[[Category:British sports television series]]\n[[Category:English football on television]]\n[[Category:English Football League on television]]\n[[Category:Football media in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Premier League on television]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the US version|Match of the Day (US TV series)|the Doctor Who novel|Match of the Day (novel)|the Genesis song|Spot the Pigeon}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Match of the Day\n| image                    = Match of the Day.png\n| caption                  = \n| show_name_2              = MOTD\n| genre                    = [[Association football|Football]] highlights and [[sports analyst|analysis]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007t9y1|title=Genre}}</ref>\n| presenter                = '''Current:'''<br>[[Gary Lineker]] (1999\u2013present)<br><br>'''Stand-in:'''<br>[[Mark Chapman (broadcaster)|Mark Chapman]]<br>[[Gabby Logan]]<br>[[Dan Walker (broadcaster)|Dan Walker]]<br><br>'''Former:'''<br>[[Kenneth Wolstenholme]] (1964\u20131967)<br>[[David Coleman]] (1967\u20131973)<br>[[Jimmy Hill]] (1973\u20131988)<br>[[Des Lynam]] (1988\u20131999)\n| starring                 = '''Predominant analysts:'''<br>''(2019\u201320 season)''<br>[[Jermaine Jenas]]<br>[[Danny Murphy (footballer, born 1977)|Danny Murphy]]<br>[[Alan Shearer]]<br>[[Ian Wright]]\n| judges                   = \n| voices                   = '''Predominant commentators:'''<br>''(2019\u201320 season)''<br>[[Steve Bower]]<br>[[Simon Brotherton]]<br>[[Guy Mowbray]] <br>[[Jonathan Pearce]]<br>[[Steve Wilson (football commentator)|Steve Wilson]]\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = Barry Stoller<ref name=lovetv>{{cite web |last=Stoller |first=Barry |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tv/entries/514c3b7e-65be-3fd6-8cf6-31fe89e4bba4 |title=Match Of The Day At 50: My iconic theme even has a banjo |date=2014-08-22 |access-date=2018-09-16 |df=dmy-all |work=Love TV |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref>\n| opentheme                = [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01g6g0g ''Match of the Day'' theme]\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_series               = 51\n| num_episodes             = Over 5,000\n| list_episodes            = \n| producer                 = Sarah Williams\n| location                 = Studio TC5, [[BBC Television Centre]] (1964\u20132011)<br>[[Dock10 (television facility)|dock10 studios]] (2011\u20132020)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dock10.co.uk/thestudios/|title=Match of the Day Studio}}</ref>\n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = Richard Hughes\n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = Live: 160-210 minutes <br> Highlights: 60\u2013105 minutes\n| company                  = [[BBC Sport]]\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = {{start date|1964|08|22|df=yes}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = {{ubl|''[[Match of the Day 2]]''|''Match of the Day 2 Extra'' |''Match of the Day 3''|''[[Match of the Day Kickabout]]''|''Match of the Day Live''|''[[Match of the Day from Northern Ireland|Match of the Day Northern Ireland]]''|''Match of the Day Wales''|''[[Match of the Day (American TV series)|Match of the Day (US)]]''|''[[The Football League Show]]''}}\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/matchoftheday\n| website_title            = ''Match of the Day''\n| channel                  = {{ubl|[[BBC One|BBC 1/One]] (1965\u2013present)|[[BBC Two|BBC 2]] (1964\u20131965)}}<!-- 'BBC One/Two' only dates from 1997. -->\n}}\n\n'''''Match of the Day''''' is a \"[[Association football|football]] highlights and [[sports analyst|analysis]]\" programme, typically broadcast on [[BBC One]] on Saturday evenings, during the [[Premier League]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007t9y1|title=About Match of the Day}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' recognised ''Match of the Day'' \"as the longest-running football [[television program]]me in the world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32850689|title=Match of the Day named world's longest-running football show|work=[[BBC Sport]]|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref> It is one of the BBC's longest-running shows, having been on air since 22 August 1964.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== 1960s ===\nAlthough the title was first used by the [[BBC]] for its [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] [[tennis]] highlights programme in June 1964, the first football-related edition of ''Match of the Day'' was screened on [[BBC Two]] on 22 August 1964, and showed highlights of a game between [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at [[Anfield]]. The programme's audience was estimated at only 20,000, less than half of the attendance at the ground.<ref name=\"bbchist\">{{cite web |title=History of Match of the Day |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tv_and_radio/match_of_the_day/879960.stm |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=14 February 2003 |access-date=26 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Match of the Day'' was not universally welcomed in the football world; in 1965 several clubs attempted to block a renewed deal with the BBC in fear of a drop in gate attendances at matches.<ref name=\"Facts\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28867419 |title=Match of the Day: 50 years of broadcasting celebration |work= [[BBC Sport]] |date=20 August 2014 |access-date=29 January 2015}}</ref> Eventually, a compromise was reached where the BBC agreed not to reveal which match was to be shown until after the day's play had concluded. The first [[color television|colour]] edition of ''Match of the Day'' on [[BBC One|BBC 1]] was shown on 15 November 1969, where it featured a game between [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. However, the very first [[color television|colour]] edition was shown on 2 November 1968 on [[BBC Two|BBC 2]] when a game between [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] was featured.<ref name=\"Facts\" /><ref name=\"bbcages\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/match_of_the_day/3135723.stm | title=MOTD through the ages | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=3 August 2004 | access-date=12 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== 1970s and 1980s ===\n[[Slow motion]] replays were first introduced in 1969.<ref name=\"bbchist\" /> However, at the end of the decade the BBC lost a significant share of matches, with a new four-year deal in 1979 splitting the rights between the BBC and [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] (ITV had originally won exclusive rights, but a ruling from the [[Office of Fair Trading]] ordered that the rights be split<ref name=\"bbcages\" />). ''Match of the Day'' was moved to Sunday afternoons for the [[1980-81 in English football|1980\u201381]] and [[1982-83 in English football|1982\u201383]] seasons.\n\nIn 1983, the programme reverted to being shown on Saturday night, although that year four broadcasts were lost due to industrial action.<ref name=\"bbchist\" /> The season 1983\u201384 also saw the first ''Match of the Day Live'' broadcasts of First Division matches, beginning with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] vs [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on 16 December \u2013 a Friday evening fixture. This came some two months after the start of [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]'s ''[[The Big Match|Big Match Live]]''.\n\n=== 1990s and 2000s ===\nLeague football highlights were not available to the [[BBC]] from 1988 as ITV had exclusive rights, though the programme remained on air for the [[FA Cup]] as ''Match of the Day: The Road to Wembley''. League football returned in 1992, for the start of the [[Premier League]] era.<ref name=\"Facts\" /> [[Sky Sports|Sky's]] emergence made the TV rights market more competitive, with the BBC losing [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]] matches after [[UEFA]]'s revamping as the Champions League in 1992, although it did broadcast the [[1994 UEFA Champions League Final|1994 final]] between [[A.C. Milan]] and [[FC Barcelona]]. In 1997, the BBC lost all live rights to the [[FA Cup]] meaning the programme's live coverage was restricted to the [[UEFA Cup]] and [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]] matches, the latter competition becoming defunct in 1999. However, the BBC were still able to show Saturday evening highlights of FA Cup games. A significant change occurred in 2001 when the Premier League awarded highlights rights to ITV in a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/fa_carling_premiership/791268.stm |title=BBC 'sour' over football deal |work=[[BBC News]] |date=15 June 2000 |access-date=29 January 2015}}</ref> Between 2001 and 2004, the ''Match of the Day'' brand was used for the BBC's live football coverage and the network had earned some consolation in losing by managing to regain live terrestrial coverage of the FA Cup and [[England national football team|England]] internationals for that period.\n\nRights for [[UEFA Champions League]] qualifiers, which are held by the home team and fall outside the rights for the competition proper, were obtained on an ad hoc basis for English teams in this period, which is currently the case for the BBC with Scottish and Northern Irish teams. Both legs of Manchester United's 2002\u201303 third round qualifying matches against [[Zalaegerszegi TE|Zalaegerszeg]] were shown live on the BBC.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/aug/04/sport.comment3 |title=Beeb muscle in on United action |first=Jon |last=Henderson |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |location=[[London]] |date=4 August 2002 |accessdate=28 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2003, it was announced that from the 2004\u201305 season, Premier League highlights were returning to the BBC and a revived ''MOTD''.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Premiership back on the BBC |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/3134163.stm |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=8 August 2003 |access-date=24 March 2016}}</ref> In addition, ''[[Match of the Day 2]]'' was launched, which showed highlights of the increasing number of Sunday fixtures, and was initially presented by [[Adrian Chiles]].<ref name=\"Facts\" />\n\nIn 2009, the BBC announced they had retained their Premier League rights, allowing them to continue showing ''Match of the Day'' until 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/7856459.stm |title=BBC retains Premier League rights |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=28 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== 2010s ===\nFrom the [[2011\u201312 Premier League|2011\u201312 season]], a new web-only ''Match of the Day 3'' programme was launched on Monday mornings as a light-hearted addition to ''[[Match of the Day 2]]''. Although broadcast as a separate programme and with its own unique title, it is recorded immediately following the conclusion of ''Match of the Day 2'' on Sunday night. In November 2011, ''Match of the Day'' moved from London to a brand new studio in [[Dock10 (television facility)|Dock10]], [[MediaCityUK]] as part of BBC Sport's relocation north, this allowed the programme to be recorded in [[high-definition video|high-definition]].<ref name=\"manchester\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mediacityuk.co.uk/occupiers/bbc |title= BBC |publisher=MediaCityUK |access-date=29 January 2015}}</ref> At the start of 2012\u201313 season ''Match of the Day 2'' moved to [[BBC One]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.premierleague.com/en-gb/news/news/2012-13/jul/match-of-the-day-two-moves-to-bbc-one.html |title=Match of the Day 2 moves to BBC One |publisher= [[Premier League]] |date= 5 July 2012 |access-date=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nUpon regaining the [[FA Cup]] rights in 2014, highlights from the early and later rounds of the competition were given their own separate programme instead of being broadcast on an extended ''Match of the Day'' straight after the [[Premier League]] highlights, as it was before the BBC last lost the rights in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b008flh8 |title=Match of the Day |work=BBC Programmes |date=1 December 2007 |access-date=31 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29410400 |title=FA Cup 2014\u201315: How to follow on the BBC |work=[[BBC Sport]] |date=4 November 2014 |access-date=31 December 2015}}</ref> Highlights of the latter rounds occasionally sequence from the Premier League highlights, as they did until the previous decade, but both segments are considered separate programmes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08jkn3d |title=Match of the Day |work= BBC Programmes |date=11 March 2017 |access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b08j246m |title=The FA Cup |work= BBC Programmes |date=11 March 2017 |access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Studio ==\nAhead of the [[2019\u201320 Premier League]] season, [[BBC Sport]] upgraded the studio that ''Match of the Day'', ''[[Match of the Day 2]]'', ''[[Football Focus]]'', and ''[[Final Score]]'' broadcasts from.\n\nThe facility uses a \"[[4K resolution|4K]] [[Ultra-high-definition television|UHD]] ready [[virtual studio|virtual reality studio]].\" It uses [[Epic Games|Epic Games']] [[Unreal_Engine#Unreal_Engine_4|Unreal Engine 4]] [[rendering (computer graphics)|rendering]] technology.\n\nFilming is located at the [[Dock10 (television facility)|Dock10]] studios at [[MediaCityUK]] in [[Salford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/tech-innovation/match-of-the-day-moves-into-dock10s-vr-studio/5141941.article|title=Match of the Day Moves Into Dock10\u2019s VR Studio}}</ref>\n\n== Presenters, analysts, and commentators ==\n[[Gary Lineker]] has served as the main presenter since 1999, having worked as an [[sports analyst|analyst]] during predecessor [[Des Lynam|Des Lynam's]] tenure.  [[Mark Chapman (broadcaster)|Mark Chapman]], [[Gabby Logan]], and [[Dan Walker (broadcaster)|Dan Walker]], have all stood-in for Lineker.\n\nThe predominant analysts for the [[2019\u201320 Premier League|2019\u201320 season]] are: [[Jermaine Jenas]], [[Danny Murphy (footballer, born 1977)|Danny Murphy]], [[Alan Shearer]], and [[Ian Wright]].  Each show typically features two analysts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007t9y1/episodes/guide|title=Presenters and analysts}}</ref>\n\n''Match of the Day'' uses a selection of [[BBC]] and [[freelancer|freelance]] [[sports commentator|commentators]], including: [[Steve Bower]], [[Simon Brotherton]], [[Guy Mowbray]], [[Jonathan Pearce]], and [[Steve Wilson (football commentator)|Steve Wilson]].\n\nIn April 2007, it was announced that [[Jacqui Oatley]] was to become the first woman to commentate on the programme.<ref name=\"Facts\" /><ref>{{cite news |title='Match of the Day' gets first woman commentator |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUKL198437520070419 | publisher=[[Reuters]] | date=2007-04-19 |access-date=2018-09-16 |df=dmy-all |quote=Jacqui Oatley, 32, will make television history when she picks up the microphone for the BBC\u2019s flagship football show at the Premier League game between Fulham and Blackburn.}}</ref>\n\nPrevious commentators have included: [[Harry Carpenter]], [[Jon Champion]], [[Barry Davies]], [[Tony Gubba]], [[Stuart Hall (television presenter)|Stuart Hall]], [[John Motson]], [[Alan Parry]], [[Idwal Robling]], [[Gerald Sinstadt]], [[Clive Tyldesley]], and [[Alan Weeks]].\n\nIn August 2014, the [[BBC]] announced that as part of the show's 50th anniversary celebrations, [[Barry Davies]] would return to commentate for one last time.<ref name=\"Presenters\">{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0135733/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title= Match of the Day (1964\u2013 ) Full Cast & Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=29 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Barry Davies returns to Match of the Day commentary box | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28881806 | work=[[BBC Sport]] | date=21 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n[[The Daily Mail]] referred to a 'tired and out of date' format compared to [[Sky Sports]]' football coverage and that new, more enthusiastic pundits are required, with the atmosphere between the current presenter and pundits deemed \"an old boy's club.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=King |first=Dominic |url=https://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2266357/Match-Day-debate--needs-change-close-gap-Sky-Sports.html |title=Colin Murray has gone... but does Match of the Day need a proper shake-up to close the gap on the champions at Sky Sports?| newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |publisher=[[DMG Media]] |location=[[London]] |date=2013-01-22 |access-date=2018-09-16 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |last=Williamson |first=Laura |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2245600/Match-Day-old-boys-club--Laura-Williamson.html |title=Wake up Gary, or Match of the Day's old boys' club may close for good |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |publisher=[[DMG Media]] |location=[[London]] |date=2012-12-09 |access-date=2013-01-23 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]]' [[United States men's national soccer team|American]] goalkeeper [[Marcus Hahnemann]] criticised the show for showing bias towards the bigger clubs in the Premier League, particularly [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Laughlin |first=Andrew |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/media/news/a277767/wolves-keeper-hits-out-at-motd-coverage/ |title=Wolves keeper hits out at MOTD coverage |date=2010-09-20 |access-date=2018-09-16| df=dmy-all|website=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]] |quote=According to Mirror Football, the American keeper is boycotting the BBC's Match Of The Day programme in protest at its portrayal of his team. Hahnemann claims that Wolves are always pushed down to the latter games shown on the Saturday night show, rather than being given top billing.}}</ref>\n\n== Premier League broadcast rights ==\n=== 2019\u201320 to 2021\u201322 seasons ===\nIn January 2018, the [[Premier League]] announced that it had awarded the UK highlights to BBC Sport. The rights cost \u00a3211.5 million and covers three seasons from 2019-20.\n\nThe January 2018 agreement also includes ''[[Match of the Day 2]]'', ''Match of the Day 2 Extra'', ''[[Match of the Day Kickabout]]'', ''[[Football Focus]]'', ''[[Final Score]]'', and ''[[The Premier League Show]]''.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/605627|title=Premier League awards UK highlights to BBC Sport (2019-2022) |publisher=[[Premier League]] |access-date=2018-09-16 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Theme music==<!-- This section is linked from [[Joxer Goes to Stuttgart]] -->\nThe current theme tune for the series is called \"Match of the Day\" and was written for the programme in 1970 by Barry Stoller. Ironically, Stoller himself admitted that he is not a football fan.{{cn|date=September 2017}}\n\nStoller's brief was simply to write \"something good\"; the short closing fanfare occurred to him first.  \"Those fanfare harmonies give the music a gladiator feel,\" he wrote in 2014, \"akin to entering the ancient games arena in Rome with all its expectations.\"  The tune was recorded by him, a trumpeter, and a drummer (Stuart Vincent) in the basement recording studio of his home.<ref name=lovetv/> In May 2010, [[PRS for Music]] revealed that the ''Match of the Day'' theme tune is the most recognisable in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sayid |first=Ruki |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv-entertainment/2010/05/11/motd-tops-tv-theme-tunes-table-115875-22249796/ |title=Match of the Day voted the most recognisable theme tune on TV |work=[[Daily Mirror]] |publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]] |location=[[London]] |date=11 May 2010 |access-date=17 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe theme is often incorrectly labelled \"Off Side\", the group name of an alternative 1970 version which was released as a [[Single (music)#7-inch_format|45 rpm gramophone single]] on the [[Pye Records|Pye]] label (7N 25534), arranged and conducted by [[Mandy Brewer]].<ref name=\"bbcages\" /> The original theme tune, entitled \"Drum Majorette\", was written by Major [[Oleen Wrigley]], the band leader of the [[Jade Petherick]] under the pen-name 'Arnold Stock'.<ref name=\"bbcages\" />\n\n== Related shows ==\n*Since 1998, the BBC's coverages of the [[FIFA World Cup]] and the [[UEFA European Championship]] have been under the ''Match of the Day'' banner.\n*Between 1995 and 1999, the BBC broadcast ''Match of the Seventies'' (1995\u201396), ''Match of the Eighties'' (1997) and ''Match of the Nineties'' (1999). Each series acted as a chronological review of seasons through each decade, presented in a slightly off-beat style, and relied heavily on footage originally included in ''Match of the Day'' broadcasts. Presenters included [[Dennis Waterman]], [[Danny Baker]], [[Mark Radcliffe (radio broadcaster)|Mark Radcliffe]], and [[Marc Riley]].\n*From the [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305 season]], a second programme, ''[[Match of the Day 2]]'', usually airs on the following Sunday.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Match of the Day |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2004/07_july/24/motd.shtml |work=Press Office |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=2004-07-24 |access-date=2018-03-31 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*From the [[2009\u201310 in English football|2009\u201310 season]] until [[2015\u201316 in English football|2015\u201316]], the BBC picked up the rights for the Football League highlights and up until [[2011\u201312 in English football|2011\u201312]], ten live [[Football League Championship|Championship]] games and three live [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] games.  Live games were broadcast under the ''Match of the Day Live'' banner but highlights were shown on a new dedicated programme named ''[[The Football League Show]]'' (or, for League Cup games, ''The League Cup Show'').\n*From the [[2013\u201314 in English football|2013\u201314 season]], American channel [[NBCSN]] has broadcast its own version also called ''[[Match of the Day (American TV series)|Match of the Day]]''.\n*From the [[2016\u201317 in English football|2016\u201317 season]], ''[[The Premier League Show]]'' typically airs on Thursday nights during the Premier League season.\n\n== Match of the Day Annual ==\nA ''Match of the Day Annual'' book is also produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcshop.com/sport/match-of-the-day-annual-2012-the-best-footy-annual-hardback/invt/9781849902397/|title=Match of the Day Annual 2012: The Best Footy Annual! (Hardback)|work=BBC Shop|access-date=23 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{Cite book |title=Match of the Day \u2013 The Complete Record since 1964 |last=Motson |first=John |authorlink=John Motson |year=1992 |publisher=[[BBC Books]] |isbn=0-563-36406-8}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|BBC|English football}}\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* [http://www.chrishunt.biz/features13.html Behind the scenes with the ''Match of the Day'' commentary team]\n* {{IMDb title|0135733|Match of the Day}}\n* {{tv.com show|match-of-the-day|Match of the Day}}\n\n{{Match of the Day}}\n{{Association football on television}}\n\n[[Category:1964 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1960s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:1970s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:1980s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:1990s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:2000s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British sports television series]]\n[[Category:BBC Sport]]\n[[Category:BBC Television programmes]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white British television programmes]]\n[[Category:British sports television series]]\n[[Category:English football on television]]\n[[Category:English Football League on television]]\n[[Category:Football media in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Premier League on television]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7d:44df:4300:3098:2873:4e06:4276", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Match_of_the_Day"}
{"title_page": "Abrol", "text_new": "'''Abrol''' is a surname.{{r|\"Hanks Coates McClure 2016\"}} The Abrol caste belongs to kshatriya (Khatri) clan and are hindus. The Abrols predominantly landlords in areas of Northwestern punjab mostly Sialkot, Present-Day Kashmir and nearby regions. Notable people with the surname include:\n\n* [[Mohit Abrol]], Indian television actor\n* [[Zahid Abrol]] (born 1950), Indian poet\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Hanks Coates McClure 2016\">{{cite book\n| last        = Hanks\n| first       = P.\n| last2       = Coates\n| first2      = R.\n| last3       = McClure\n| first3      = P.\n| title       = The Oxford Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland\n| publisher   = OUP Oxford\n| year        = 2016\n| isbn        = 978-0-19-252747-9\n| url         = https://books.google.com/books?id=0AyDDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA7\n| access-date = 3 September 2018\n| page        = 7\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Surname}}\n", "text_old": "'''Abrol''' is a surname.{{r|\"Hanks Coates McClure 2016\"}} The surname belongs to kshatriya clan and are hindus. They may also belong to Jatt clan, predominantly landlords in areas of Present-Day Kashmir and nearby regions. Notable people with the surname include:\n\n* [[Mohit Abrol]], Indian television actor\n* [[Zahid Abrol]] (born 1950), Indian poet\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Hanks Coates McClure 2016\">{{cite book\n| last        = Hanks\n| first       = P.\n| last2       = Coates\n| first2      = R.\n| last3       = McClure\n| first3      = P.\n| title       = The Oxford Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland\n| publisher   = OUP Oxford\n| year        = 2016\n| isbn        = 978-0-19-252747-9\n| url         = https://books.google.com/books?id=0AyDDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA7\n| access-date = 3 September 2018\n| page        = 7\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Surname}}\n", "name_user": "106.205.98.17", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abrol"}
{"title_page": "Natasia Demetriou", "text_new": "{{short description|British comedian, actress, and screenwriter}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Natasia Demetriou\n| image              = Natasia Demetriou.jpg\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = 1984<ref name=\"DB\"/>\n| birth_place        = [[London]], England\n\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| caption            = Demetriou in 2019\n| relatives          = [[Jamie Demetriou]] (brother)\n| occupation         = Comedian, actress, screenwriter\n}}\n\n'''Natasia Charlotte Demetriou''' is an English-Cypriot comedian, actress and screenwriter. She is best known for her role as Nadja in the 2019 [[What We Do in the Shadows (TV series)|TV adaptation]] of the film ''[[What We Do in the Shadows]].''\n\n==Early Life==\n\nDemetriou is an English-Cypriot raised in North London,<ref name=\"celebability\">{{cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/celebability/episodes/3/ |title=CelebAbility Series 3, Episode 3|date=19 June 2019|network=[[ITV2]]|series=[[Iain Stirling]]'s CelebAbility |work=comedy.co.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"nerv\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/oct/22/natasia-demetriou-most-nervous-standup-comedian-invisible-dot|title=Natasia Demetriou \u2013 comedy's most nervous standup?|first=Ryan|last=Gilbey|date=22 October 2014|work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref> born in 1984 she is the older sister to Jamie Demetriou, who is also a comedian, actor, and screenwriter. Their father Sotiris, is a chef.<ref name=\"DB\">{{cite web | url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/stath-lets-flats-jamie-natasia-demetriou-comedy-channel-4-279991 | title=Jamie and Natasia Demetriou: 'Our spirit animal is a Muppet with its mouth open' | publisher=[[i (newspaper)]] | date=6 September 2019 | accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref> She went to [[Bristol University]] where alongside her brother she was a member of [[Bristol Revunions]]\u2019 sketch troupe, ''Comedy Biscuit'', who received critical acclaim at [[Edinburgh Fringe]] 2009-2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/2t2xQ2CbbhGBDs4XXLCZbGJ/jamie-demetriou|title=Comedy At The Fringe - Jamie Demetriou - BBC Three|website=BBC}}</ref> She worked as nanny while doing \u201ccomedy gigging and Edinburgh\u201d.<ref name=\"mfm\">{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/natasia-demetriou-interview-what-we-do-in-the-shadows-bbc-sketch-shows-comedy-sexism-a8946396.html | title=Natasia Demetriou: \u2018Music, fashion and media all push the idea that women are more attractive if they look like little girls\u2019 | publisher=The Independent | date=11 June 2019 | accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShe is a comedian, actress, and screenwriter.<ref name=\"card\">{{cite web|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160405065326/https://www.latitudefestival.com/line-up/artist/cardinal-burns-jamie-demetriou-natasia-demetriou-ellie-white-special-guests |title=Cardinal Burns, Jamie Demetriou, Natasia Demetriou, Ellie White & Special Guests|date=23 March 2016|publisher=latitudefestival.com}}</ref> Her debut show, ''You'll Never Have All of Me'', won the [[The Skinny (magazine)|''Skinny'']] Debutant Award at the 2014 [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unitedagents.co.uk/natasia-demetriou|title=Natasia Demetriou - United Agents|publisher=}}</ref> She was a longtime member of [[sketch comedy]] troupe Oyster Eyes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theskinny.co.uk/festivals/edinburgh-fringe/comedy/natasia-demetriou-doin-it-for-the-laughs|title=Natasia Demetriou: Doin' It for the Laughs - Interview - The Skinny|publisher=}}</ref> and has written for ''[[Anna & Katy]]'' and ''[[The Midnight Beast (TV series)|The Midnight Beast]].''\n\nIn 2018 she starred as her real brother Jamie\u2019s fictional on-screen sister in [[Channel 4]] [[sitcom]], [[Stath Lets Flats]], about a dysfunctional family-run estate agents.<ref name=\"mfm\"/> She has also stared in the positively regarded [[BBC Three]] comedy [[sketch show]] [[television pilot|pilot]]s the 2019 ''Ellie and Natasia'' (full of feminist fury and daft gags about social anxiety and being a woman today) and the 2015 ''People Time'' with [[Ellie White]], the later also alongside her brother Jamie.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/jun/19/ellie-and-natasia-a-fiercely-funny-sketch-show-youll-watch-over-and-over | title=Ellie and Natasia: a fiercely funny sketch show you\u2019ll watch over and over | publisher=[[The Guardian]] | date=19 June 2019 | accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"mfm\"/>\n\nDemetriou plays Nadja  a [[Romani people|Romani]] vampire, in the critically acclaimed [[BBC2]]/[[FX]] [[mockumentary]] [[Comedy horror|horror comedy series]], [[What We Do in the Shadows (TV series)]], a [[TV adaptation]] of the film ''[[What We Do in the Shadows]]''.<ref name=\"PremiereTrailer\">{{cite web |last1=Petski |first1=Denise |title='What We Do in the Shadows': FX Vampire Comedy Series Unveils Trailer, Sets Premiere Date -TCA |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/what-we-do-in-the-shadows-trailer-premiere-date-fx-vampire-comedy-series-tca-1202549095/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=February 4, 2019 |date=February 4, 2019}}</ref> The series follows four vampires sharing a house in  present day New York City, has had two seasons (2019 and 2020) so far, is written by [[Jemaine Clement]], and also stars [[Kayvan Novak]], [[Matt Berry]], [[Harvey Guill\u00e9n]] and [[Mark Proksch]].<ref name=\"PremiereTrailer\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/fx-sets-premiere-dates-for-fargo-mrs-america-better-things-devs-archer-more-tca-1202825595/ |title=FX Sets Premiere Dates For 'Fargo', 'Mrs. America', 'Better Things', 'Devs', 'Archer' & More \u2013 TCA |website=Deadline |first=Denise |last=Petski |date=January 9, 2020 |accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</r